---
const props = Astro.props;
const { data } = props;
import BeachvilleAccordionItem from "../BeachvilleAccordionItem.astro";
import BeachvilleListItem from "../BeachvilleListItem.astro";
import BeachvilleArtistSection from "../BeachvilleArtistSection.astro";
---

<div id="region-details" class="my-8" >
    
    <!-- Accordion Container -->
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto space-y-8">
      <!-- The Political Weather -->
       <BeachvilleAccordionItem title="The Political Weather">
        <div slot="icon">
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" x="0px" y="0px" width="64" height="64" viewBox="0 0 64 64" stroke="currentColor" class="w-8 h-8 text-[#064161]">
            <path d="M 29 7 C 25.686 7 23 9.686 23 13 L 15 13 C 11.686 13 9 15.686 9 19 L 9 45 C 9 48.314 11.686 51 15 51 L 49 51 C 52.314 51 55 48.314 55 45 L 55 19 C 55 15.686 52.314 13 49 13 L 41 13 C 41 9.686 38.314 7 35 7 L 29 7 z M 29 11 L 35 11 C 36.104 11 37 11.895 37 13 L 27 13 C 27 11.895 27.896 11 29 11 z M 15 17 L 49 17 C 50.105 17 51 17.895 51 19 L 51 27.328125 C 47.860304 27.865386 40.276945 29 32 29 C 23.725715 29 16.142076 27.866066 13 27.328125 L 13 19 C 13 17.895 13.895 17 15 17 z M 13 31.384766 C 15.851521 31.855688 20.994182 32.574326 27 32.865234 L 27 33 C 27 34.105 27.895 35 29 35 L 34 35 C 35.105 35 36 34.105 36 33 L 36 32.917969 C 42.43805 32.665598 47.988855 31.881828 51 31.384766 L 51 45 C 51 46.105 50.105 47 49 47 L 15 47 C 13.895 47 13 46.105 13 45 L 13 31.384766 z"></path>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div slot="content">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
                          The 1960s across these regions were politically turbulent and transformative. <br/>
                          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">Middle East & Levant:</span> Pan-Arab nationalism under Egypt’s Gamal Abdel Nasser, coups in Syria and Iraq, and the Six-Day War (1967) defined the decade. Music was tightly monitored — songs could unify a people but also threaten regimes.
                          </div>
                          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">Iran:</span> The Shah’s modernization policies fueled a budding pop industry, even as censorship loomed.
                          </div>
                          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">Turkey:</span> Rock, jazz, and folk flourished under state tension, birthing unique fusions.
                          </div>
                          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">Asia:</span> Postcolonial identity shaped the region — India and Pakistan leaned into music as a modern-traditional bridge, while Southeast Asia absorbed US rock.
                          </div>
                          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">China:</span> The Cultural Revolution (1966 onward) suppressed almost all traditional/popular music in favor of revolutionary operas.
                          </div>
                          <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">Japan & East Asia:</span> Postwar booms opened doors to Western imports and experimental fusions.
                          </div>
                          <br/>
              Across the board, music was not just entertainment but part of identity, protest, propaganda, or cultural renewal.
                          
          </div>

        </div>
       </BeachvilleAccordionItem>

       <!-- What People Were Hearing -->
       <BeachvilleAccordionItem title="What People Were Hearing (Before the 60s)">
        <div slot="icon">
          <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 19V6l12-3v13M9 19c0 1.105-1.343 2-3 2s-3-.895-3-2 1.343-2 3-2 3 .895 3 2zm12-3c0 1.105-1.343 2-3 2s-3-.895-3-2 1.343-2 3-2 3 .895 3 2zM9 10l12-3"></path>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div slot="content">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">Middle East & North Africa (Arab):</span> Maqam traditions, Persian dastgah, Ottoman classical forms, Levantine dabke, Bedouin sung poetry, Sephardic folk. Instruments: oud, qanun, ney, darbuka, riq. Orchestras in Egypt & Lebanon already used violins/cellos with Arabic modes.  
            </div>
              
              <div class="flex flex-col items-center space-x-2">
                <img src="https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/asia_assets/content_images/OUD.jpeg" alt="Oud" class="w-36 rounded-xl h-auto">
                <span class="text-sm text-[#064161]/80">Oud</span> <br/>
              </div>
            
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">Iran & Turkey:</span> Persian classical forms + Turkish folk songs anchored daily listening.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">India:</span> Hindustani and Carnatic classical, bhajans, folk, and a booming film industry.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">Pakistan:</span> Ghazals, qawwalis, Punjabi/Sindhi folk.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">Sri Lanka:</span> Baila (Afro-Portuguese), Kandyan drumming, Buddhist chants.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">China:</span> Peking opera, revolutionary anthems.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">Japan:</span> Enka ballads.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              <span class="font-bold">SE Asia (Indonesia, Philippines, Thailand, Taiwan):</span> Gamelan, kulintang, luk thung (Thai folk-pop), ritual/tribal music.
Pakistan: Ghazals, qawwalis, Punjabi/Sindhi folk.
            </div>
          
            <div class="flex flex-col items-center space-x-2">
              <img src="https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/asia_assets/content_images/Gamelan.jpeg" alt="Gamelan" class="w-42 rounded-xl h-auto">
              <span class="text-sm text-[#064161]/80">Gamelan</span> <br/>
            </div>
By the 60s, radio, vinyl, and Western cultural imports filtered into Cairo, Beirut, Tehran, Istanbul, parts of India, Tokyo, Jakarta, and Manila. The result was traditional sounds colliding with surf rock, funk, psychedelia, and orchestral pop.

          </div>
      
        </div>  
       </BeachvilleAccordionItem>

       <!-- What you can find in this playlist -->
       <BeachvilleAccordionItem title="What to Expect in This Playlist">
        <div slot="icon">
          <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 10V3L4 14h7v7l9-11h-7z"></path>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div slot="content">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Philippines & Taiwan:" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]" image={{ src: "https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/asia_assets/content_images/Pinoy.jpeg", alt: "Philippines and Taiwan", width: "w-64", caption: "Philippines and Taiwan" }} >
              <div slot="content">
                Rock & roll arrived in Manila and Taipei through surf riffs, twangy guitars, and backbeat-driven teen dance tunes. In the Philippines, garage-style rawness crept in, with fuzz pedals and Tagalog lyrics turning Western rock into something earthier. Taiwan’s scene leaned on crooner charm but got recharged by rock rhythms, giving Mandarin pop a sharper, beat-band edge.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>
            
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Indonesia:" borderColor="border-[#C13870]" >
              <div slot="content">
                Despite government bans, Jakarta’s underground was buzzing. Bands snuck Western rock into dancehalls, distorting guitars through cheap amps, creating a ragged, fuzz-heavy sound that felt illicit and alive.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>

            <BeachvilleListItem title="Thailand:" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]" image={{ src: "https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/asia_assets/content_images/sound_of_siam.jpeg", alt: "Sound of Siam", width: "w-64", caption: "Sound of Siam" }} >
              <div slot="content">
                Local genres like molam and luk thung fused with wah-wah guitars, brass, and James Brown-inspired funk. The result was deeply danceable but still rooted in Thai melodic traditions. Side by side with this were raw beat groups covering Western hits with wild fuzz and cheeky attitude. Sound of Siam is a great compilation that covers a lot of this
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>

            <BeachvilleListItem title="Cambodia:" borderColor="border-[#C13870]" >
              <div slot="content">
                Cambodian pop blurred psychedelic garage rock with the country’s distinct pentatonic folk melodies. Soul grooves and Farfisa organs sat comfortably alongside traditional ornamentation, producing a bittersweet but electrified sound.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>

            <BeachvilleListItem title="Japan:" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]" >
              <div slot="content">
                Sugar-sweet vocal pop coexisted with a growing underground of heavy psych. On one end: glossy harmonies and chanson-like ballads, often tied to film culture. On the other: searing fuzz guitar, avant-garde noise, and a jazz underground that was already reaching toward free improvisation.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>

            <BeachvilleListItem title="China & Hong Kong:" borderColor="border-[#C13870]" >
              <div slot="content">
                Cabaret and nightclub sounds shaped much of the music here: swing, cha-cha, and mambo colliding with Mandarin and Cantonese pop melodies. These hybrids sounded glamorous yet restless, as East Asian pop absorbed Western rhythms in smoky dancehalls.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>

            <BeachvilleListItem title="India:" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]" >
              <div slot="content">
                Bollywood and South Indian film studios became laboratories for sound—layering sitar, tabla, and Carnatic ragas with big-band jazz, Moogs, and surf-inspired guitar licks. The orchestration was lush but adventurous, reshaping film music into psychedelic, technicolor experiments.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>

            <BeachvilleListItem title="Iran, Egypt & Turkey:" borderColor="border-[#C13870]" image={{ src: "https://syvkefpljdcoricvmqcy.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/images/asia_assets/content_images/ANatoly.jpeg", alt: "Anatolian rock artists", width: "w-80", caption: "Anatolian rock artists" }} >
              <div slot="content">
                Across West Asia and North Africa, rock and jazz mingled with local scales and rhythms. In Tehran, fuzz guitars threaded through Persian modes. In Cairo, jazz orchestras locked onto Afro-Arab grooves. In Istanbul, psychedelic organ lines tangled with Anatolian folk, sparking the birth of a truly hybrid rock language.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>


          


          </div>
          
        </div>
       </BeachvilleAccordionItem>
       <!-- Tech Factor -->
       <BeachvilleAccordionItem title="Tech Factor">
        <div slot="icon">
          <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9.75 17L9 20l-1 1h8l-1-1-.75-3M3 13h18M5 17h14a2 2 0 002-2V5a2 2 0 00-2-2H5a2 2 0 00-2 2v10a2 2 0 002 2z"></path>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div slot="content">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            <BeachvilleListItem title="Amplification & Radio:" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]" >
              <div slot="content">
                Radios spread state broadcasts (Umm Kulthum in Egypt, Tarab in Syria, Bollywood hits in India).
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>

            <BeachvilleListItem title="Electric Instruments:" borderColor="border-[#C13870]" >
              <div slot="content">
                Fenders, Mosrites, Farfisa organs, fuzz pedals spread to Istanbul, Tehran, Tokyo, Manila, Jakarta.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>

            <BeachvilleListItem title="Recording Studios:" borderColor="border-[#FEE96A]" >
              <div slot="content">
                Cairo, Beirut, Tehran, Bombay, Tokyo emerged as hubs.
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>

            <BeachvilleListItem title="Fusion Experiments:" borderColor="border-[#C13870]" >

              <div slot="content">
              
              <p>  Oud + saxophone (Egypt, Lebanon).</p>
              <p>  Sitar + electric guitar (India).</p>
              <p>  Saz + fuzz pedal (Turkey).</p>
                <p>  Gamelan rhythms + psych fuzz (Indonesia).</p>
                <p>  Tabla with jazz kits (South India).</p>
              </div>
            </BeachvilleListItem>


          </div>
        </div>
       </BeachvilleAccordionItem>

       <!-- Notable Artists -->
       <BeachvilleAccordionItem title="Notable Artists">
        <div slot="icon">
          <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M16 7a4 4 0 11-8 0 4 4 0 018 0zM12 14a7 7 0 00-7 7h14a7 7 0 00-7-7z"></path>
          </svg>
        </div>
        <div slot="content" class="space-y-6">
          <BeachvilleArtistSection data={data} />
            
          </div>
        </div>
      </BeachvilleAccordionItem>


        </div>


       </BeachvilleAccordionItem>
   </div>
     
  

</div>

<script>
  // Accordion functionality
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const accordionTriggers = document.querySelectorAll('.accordion-trigger');
    
    accordionTriggers.forEach(trigger => {
      trigger.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const accordionItem = trigger.closest('.accordion-item');
        const content = accordionItem?.querySelector('.accordion-content');
        const icon = trigger.querySelector('.accordion-icon');
        
        if (content && icon) {
          const isOpen = !content.classList.contains('hidden');
          

          
          // Toggle current accordion
          if (isOpen) {
            content.classList.add('hidden');
            icon.classList.remove('rotate-180');
          } else {
            content.classList.remove('hidden');
            icon.classList.add('rotate-180');
          }
        }
      });
    });
  });
</script>


